  "prompt": "How do you treat acne on your arms?",
  "response": "Treating acne on your arms involves a combination of good skincare practices, over-the-counter treatments, and lifestyle adjustments. Here are some steps that can help:\n\n1. **Gentle Cleansing:**\n   - Use a gentle, fragrance-free cleanser to wash your arms daily. Avoid harsh soaps that can irritate the skin.\n\n2. **Exfoliation:**\n   - Exfoliate your skin 1-2 times a week with a mild scrub or a product containing salicylic acid or glycolic acid. This can help unclog pores and remove dead skin cells.\n\n3. **Topical Treatments:**\n   - Apply over-the-counter creams or gels containing benzoyl peroxide, salicylic acid, or alpha hydroxy acids to treat and prevent acne.\n   - For sensitive skin, start with a lower concentration to see how your skin reacts.\n\n4. **Moisturizing:**\n   - Use a non-comedogenic moisturizer to keep your skin hydrated, especially if you\u2019re using topical treatments that can dry out the skin.\n\n5. **Clothing Choices:**\n   - Wear loose-fitting, breathable fabrics to reduce irritation and sweat accumulation on the skin.\n\n6. **Shower After Sweating:**\n   - Shower promptly after activities that cause you to sweat to prevent sweat from clogging pores.\n\n7. **Avoid Picking:**\n   - Don't pick or squeeze acne, as this can lead to scarring and further irritation.\n\n8. **Healthy Diet and Hydration:**\n   - Maintain a balanced diet and stay hydrated to support overall skin health.\n\n9. **Consider Allergies:**\n   - Be mindful of any products or environmental factors that might trigger acne or irritation, such as laundry detergents or fabric softeners.\n\nIf your arm acne persists or is particularly severe, it might be a good idea to consult a dermatologist. They can offer prescription treatments like topical or oral antibiotics, retinoids, or other medications.",
